      <strong>Practice Tip:</strong> When you encounter っ while reading, tap your finger on the desk for that beat. One tap per mora — including the silent っ mora. This physical cue helps your internal sense of Japanese rhythm develop much faster.
    </div>

    <h2 id="combo-sounds">Combination Sounds: ゃ ゅ ょ</h2>
    <p>These small characters combine with い-column characters (き, し, ち, に, ひ, み, り, and their voiced equivalents) to create single blended syllables called yoon (拗音). For example, き (ki) + ゃ (ya) becomes きゃ (kya) — one syllable, not two. The small kana is swallowed into the preceding consonant.</p>
    <p>Real-world examples: <strong>きょう</strong> (kyou, today), <strong>しゃしん</strong> (shashin, photo), <strong>りょうり</strong> (ryouri, cooking), <strong>ちょっと</strong> (chotto, a little — combines both っ and ょ), <strong>にゅうがく</strong> (nyuugaku, school enrollment).</p>

